=E1=E5=E0 =F0=F2=F9=E4 =F9=E9=E7=E4 =F2=ED =E0=E3=ED =EE=E7=F8 =E0=ED =F0=
=E5=E7 =EC=EB=ED





Up to that date you are taxable on UK assets and gains and any foreign inco=
me and gains (FIG) remitted to the UK. The definition of a remittance is wi=
de and includes constructive remittances.



From 6 April 2025 you will be taxable on your worldwide income and gains on=
 the arising basis, plus the remittance of any FIG that arose whilst you we=
re UK resident and claiming the remittance basis. You have advised that, at=
 the latest, 2026/27 will be your final year of UK residence.



For CGT, the base cost of your shares is the original acquisition cost, tha=
t is, there was no-rebasing to market value at 2 January 2018 when you were=
 treated as arriving in the UK. However, if relevant, for disposals after 5=
 April 2025, the 5 April 2017 market value will be substituted for market v=
alue for investments acquired before that date but you have the option to e=
lect that original cost be used instead on a share by share basis.



Also, your broker should be familiar with the CGT identification rules but =
I will repeat them here. Normally, multiple acquisitions of the same holdin=
g are averaged (or pooled) for the purpose of matching with disposals. Ther=
e are two exceptions which take precedence: (1) same day disposals and acqu=
isitions are matched with each other and then (2) disposals are matched wit=
h any acquisitions in the following 30-day period (known as =93bed and brea=
kfasting=94). What this means is that if you sell an investment and then re=
-acquire it on the same day or within 30 days thereafter, the re-acquisitio=
n is matched with the disposal, normally resulting in a minimal gain or los=
s, leaving the carried forward investment with the original acquisition cos=
t.



Where it is advisable for tax purposes to sell an investment to realise a g=
ain (or a loss) but you would like to retain an investment, to avoid the id=
entification rules above consider buying it in one of your overseas trusts.=
 As mentioned to you, the trust positions are complicated and we recommend =
obtaining further advice from Tax Counsel. The corollary is buying personal=
ly where you need to sell an asset in one of the trusts. If that is not pos=
sible a more complicated solution is as follows:



  *   Following the realisation of capital gains this tax year, consider ac=
quiring your and your wife=92s new investments in separate portfolios to fa=
cilitate retaining future investments that you may want to sell after 5 Apr=
il 2025 to crystalise a loss but would still like to retain. Also transfer =
your retained 50% holdings to each other so that each investment is just he=
ld by one of you but you can retain broadly equal portfolios by value. This=
 is because if you and your wife have separate portfolios you can sell an a=
sset in one portfolio and then purchase it in the other portfolio so that t=
he same day and bed and breakfasting rules do not apply. The sales and purc=
hases must be on the open market as an inter-spouse disposal is treated as =
a non-gain no loss transfer. The downside is complication and, although it =
will not be your intention to realise gains after 5 April 2025 that may be =
unavoidable, you could end up with gains in one portfolio and losses in the=
 other which cannot be offset against each other. Where that is going to be=
 the case it should be possible for you beforehand to transfer holdings and=
 then sell so that net gains do not arise in one portfolio. There is some a=
nti-avoidance to restrict losses where there are arrangements and a maim pu=
rpose is to secure a tax advantage. However, HMRC guidance says this is unl=
ikely to apply to the steps mentioned above unless the repurchased shares a=
re transferred back to the first spouse with the original holding as that w=
ould result in a tax loss but no economic loss to the first spouse.



Our advice is predicated on the basis that all your investments are non-UK =
source/situs. However, the investments can be =A3sterling denominated. Also=
, see below regarding the purchase and sale of QCBs.



Furthermore, we are not IFAs and our advice is provided for the purposes of=
 minimising your UK tax liabilities and we cannot advise you on what invest=
ments to buy and sell.





Up to 5 April 2025



  *   Maximise FIG. This includes the selling of bonds to realise both the =
gains and accrued interest.
  *   Do not realise capital losses.
  *   Claim the remittance basis on your 2024/25 tax return and pay the rem=
ittance basis charge for 2024/25.
  *   The bed and breakfasting rules need to be borne in mind for the curre=
nt disposals being made =96 the same investment should not be reacquired wi=
thin 30 days. Instead, consider use of one of the overseas trusts to re-acq=
uire the asset and vice-versa, that is, the trust sells and independently y=
ou buy the same stock





After 5 April 2025



  *   Minimise FIG.
  *   Defer income to when no longer UK resident. This is best achieved by =
investing in funds/mutuals so you can dictate when to sell. However, they s=
hould be Non-Reporting funds to otherwise avoid taxable excess reportable i=
ncome of Reporting Funds. They can be funds were the income is retained but=
 do not invest in funds where scrip/notional dividends are used to buy addi=
tional units as those scrip/notional dividends are taxed as income.
  *   Realise losses to mitigate any gains arising. Losses are offset again=
st gains of the same tax year. Excess losses of a tax year are carried forw=
ard to the next tax year but they cannot be carried back to a prior year. S=
o timing of loss realisation may be important.





Qualifying Corporate Bonds (QCBs)



The gain on the sale of a QCB is exempt, as is a loss.



To be a QCB an investment must satisfy the following conditions:

  1.  It must have been issued after 13 March 1984
  2.  It represents a normal commercial loan
  3.  It must be denominated/expressed in =A3sterling
  4.  There must be no provision for it to be converted or redeemed in any =
other currency.



You must not buy sterling bonds of UK companies as that would constitute a =
constructive remittance. The sterling bonds should be that of non-UK compan=
ies quoted on a foreign stock exchange, for example, New York.



However, the interest receivable from a QCB is taxable.



Low coupon short dated QCBs currently valued at below par and held until ma=
turity will result in broadly a small amount of taxable income (the interes=
t payable between now and maturity) and a non-taxable gain (the difference =
between par and price paid). Both the price paid and interest received are =
reduced by any accrued interest at the purchase date.



If you or your broker require any further information or clarification of t=
he above, please let me know.



